{
  "title": "Containerizing Batch Jobs using FastAPI in Python 3.12+",
  "summary": "This explainer demonstrates how to containerize batch jobs using FastAPI, a modern web framework for building APIs in Python 3.12+. It utilizes Uvicorn as the ASGI server and Docker for containerization.",

  "key_points": [
    "FastAPI provides an easy-to-use, high-performance, web framework for building RESTful APIs in Python.",
    "Uvicorn is the recommended ASGI server for FastAPI, providing a simple way to run the application as a server within a Docker container.",
    "Docker is used for containerization, allowing the deployment of applications across different environments without worrying about compatibility issues.",
    "This setup makes it easier to manage and scale batch jobs, as they can be triggered via HTTP requests to the FastAPI endpoint."
  ],

  "code_examples": [
    {
      "language": "Python",
      "code": "from fastapi import FastAPI\napp = FastAPI()\ndef process_batch(data: list): # Your batch processing logic here\n@app.post('/process_batch/')\nasync def process_batch_endpoint():\n data = await request.json()\n return process_batch(data)\nif __name__ == '__main__':\n uvicorn.run(app, host='0.0.0.0', port=8000)"
    },
    {
      "language": "Dockerfile",
      "code": "FROM tiangolo/uvicorn-fastapi:python3.12\nWORKDIR /app\nCOPY ./ ./\nEXPOSE 8000"
    }
  ],

  "version_notes": [
    "Python version: 3.12",
    "FastAPI version: Latest compatible with Python 3.12",
    "Uvicorn version: Latest compatible with FastAPI and Python 3.12"
  ],

  "caveats": [
    "Ensure you have Docker installed on your system.",
    "Replace the `process_batch` function with your own batch processing logic.",
